\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy is the governance-level root for all Information Operations communications.
 It establishes the formal versus informal communication boundary,
 the strategic reporting cadence to County leadership,
 the operational notification standards for service availability,
 the One Voice Rule that governs incident communications,
 and the Information Exchange Agreement framework that operationalizes CJIS Security Policy Section 5.1 (Information Exchange Agreements) and NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 CA-3 (Information Exchange).
 Day-to-day service communications are governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Service Communications Policy);
 active cybersecurity incident communications are governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.06"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Communication Protocols and Partner Integration).
 Both policies incorporate the governance framework established in this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Formal vs.
 Informal Communications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
To ensure accountability,
 Information Operations shall distinguish strictly between binding and non-binding communications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Formal Communications (Binding)
\series default
:
 Written or recorded communications that create an official record,
 authorize work,
 direct action,
 commit funds,
 establish scope,
 or signify a decision.
 Examples include emails,
 memoranda,
 work orders,
 approved meeting minutes,
 status reports,
 and presentations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Informal Communications (Non-Binding)
\series default
:
 Verbal conversations,
 hallway discussions,
 non-recorded phone calls,
 text messages (SMS),
 and transient instant-messaging exchanges (including chat platforms,
 direct messages,
 and ephemeral channels).
 Informal communications shall not authorize work,
 financial commitments,
 security-impacting changes,
 or policy deviations.
 Directives received through text messages or instant-messaging channels shall be treated as verbal communications for purposes of the Written Confirmation Rule and shall be subject to the same written confirmation,
 presumption,
 escalation,
 and liability provisions established in this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Lawful Supervisory Direction
\series default
:
 All Information Operations Personnel shall comply with lawful verbal direction from their chain of command and shall pursue written confirmation under the Written Confirmation Rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Written Confirmation Rule
\series default
:
 Verbal communications involving directives,
 financial commitments,
 procurement direction,
 scope changes,
 or architectural decisions shall be reduced to writing by the end of the business day on which the verbal communication occurred.
 When the verbal communication occurs within the final two (2) hours of the business day,
 written confirmation shall be completed no later than 10:00 AM on the following business day.
 All other verbal communications requiring a record shall be reduced to writing within one (1) business day.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Presumption
\series default
:
 Verbal directives not reduced to writing within the applicable Written Confirmation Rule window are presumptively void,
 and the underlying communication shall be treated as non-binding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Escalation
\series default
:
 When the issuing authority fails to provide written confirmation within the applicable window,
 the receiving personnel shall escalate the matter through the chain of command in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Liability
\series default
:
 All Information Operations Personnel shall not execute financial,
 procurement,
 or scope-changing directives that have not been reduced to writing within the applicable Written Confirmation Rule window.
 Action taken outside this control shall constitute non-compliance and may result in corrective action under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Strategic Reporting Cadence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director shall maintain a predictable reporting rhythm to ensure leadership visibility and alignment with County Management.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monthly Executive Report
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall provide a formal written report to the County Manager each month covering project status,
 service performance,
 budget variance,
 and emerging risks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Monthly Briefing
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall conduct a live status briefing with the County Manager each month to review the Monthly Executive Report and align priorities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Operational Communication Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information Operations shall maintain a "No Surprise" standard regarding service availability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Scheduled Maintenance
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall issue scheduled maintenance notifications no less than forty-eight (48) hours in advance of the maintenance window.
 When forty-eight (48) hours advance notice is not operationally achievable,
 the Assistant IT Director shall issue notice immediately upon scheduling and shall document the justification in the work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Unplanned Outages
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director or designated Information Operations Personnel shall issue an initial stakeholder notification within fifteen (15) minutes of confirming a widespread outage.
 For purposes of this section,
 a widespread outage is a service interruption that meets any of the following criteria:
 affects two (2) or more County departments;
 impairs a core enterprise service (including email,
 telephony,
 network connectivity,
 directory services,
 or financial and enterprise resource planning systems);
 or affects a life-safety or public-safety system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Incident,
 Media,
 and Public Communications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy establishes the One Voice Rule for incident communications.
 The execution of incident communications during active cybersecurity incident response is governed by 
