\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Information Exchange Agreements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information Exchange Agreements (IEAs) are the governance instruments through which the County authorizes,
 documents,
 and constrains the exchange of Criminal Justice Information (CJI) and other restricted data with external parties.
 This policy establishes the County standard for IEA content,
 custody,
 and retrievability,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section 5.1 (Information Exchange Agreements) and NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 CA-3 (Information Exchange).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Requirement
\series default
:
 Any arrangement that enables external access to,
 transmission of,
 or exchange of CJI shall be supported by a written Information Exchange Agreement or equivalent contract language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Required Agreement Content
\series default
:
 Information exchange documentation shall define each of the following:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Interface characteristics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Security controls implemented at each connection point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Authorized data elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Restrictions on connections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Terms and termination conditions.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Custody and Retrieval
\series default
:
 The IT Director shall ensure that executed Information Exchange Agreements are stored in the County's designated contract repository with version control,
 and that any executed Information Exchange Agreement is retrievable within one (1) business day upon request.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Public Records Awareness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All Information Operations Personnel shall compose formal communications with the awareness that such records may be subject to disclosure under NRS 239 (Public Records),
 unless protected by a specific statutory exemption or confidentiality requirement.
 The Department's documentation discipline,
 governed by 
\series bold
Policy 
